Average Cost of Home Insurance in Iowa by Coverage Amount

In Iowa, the average annual homeowners insurance premium for a policy with $250K in dwelling coverage, $125K in personal property coverage, and $200K in liability coverage is $1,828 — lower than the national average of $2,423. 

When deciding how much coverage you need, make sure your policy can fully rebuild your home and replace your belongings after a loss. For example, a policy with $100K in dwelling coverage costs about $1,080 per year, while increasing that to $500K raises the average premium to $2,918.

Average Annual Home Insurance Premium Iowa by Coverage Amount

$250K Dwelling / $125K Personal Property / $200K Liability$1,828
$500K Dwelling / $250K Personal Property / $300K Liability$2,918

Average Cost of Home Insurance in Iowa by Credit Score

Homeowners with excellent credit pay an average annual premium of $1,434 for homeowners insurance in Iowa, while those with poor credit pay $8,843. Credit scores profoundly affect insurance rates, with poor credit costing $7,015 more than the state average of $1,828.

You can't improve your credit score immediately, but you can work on it over time to lower your rates. In the short term, compare the cheapest insurers in Iowa to see which will save you the most.

Average Cost of Home Insurance in Iowa by Construction and Roof Type

Your roof type affects your homeowners insurance premium in Iowa. More durable materials like tile can reduce costs due to their longevity and resistance to damage. Homes with tile roofing average lower insurance costs compared with less durable materials such as shake-treated roofs.

Your home's construction type also affects insurance rates. Materials that offer greater resistance to common perils like fire can lead to lower premiums. Homes built with superior construction materials enjoy more favorable insurance rates than homes with standard frame construction.

Use the drop-downs in the table below to see how premiums change based on your home's materials.

Average Cost of Home Insurance in Iowa for Newly Constructed Homes

Insuring a new construction home in Iowa averages $903 annually, much lower than the $1,828 for existing homes. Average Cost of Home Insurance in Iowa by Claims History

Iowa homeowners who haven't filed claims in the past five years can expect an average annual premium of $1,828 for their insurance. If you filed one claim within the last five years, the average premium rises to $2,192 — an increase of $364 from the claim-free baseline. 

Those with two claims within the same period pay an average annual premium of $2,445 — $617 more than homeowners with no claims. Your claims history substantially affects insurance costs.

IOWA NATURAL DISASTERS AND HOME INSURANCE

In Iowa, tornadoes and flooding are the most costly natural disasters for homeowners. Tornado damage is covered by standard home insurance policies, but flooding isn't covered. You'll need separate flood insurance.

Average Cost of Home Insurance by City in Iowa

For the cities we analyzed, we found annual premiums ranging from $1,692 to $1,914. Cedar Rapids homeowners pay an average of $1,781 annually. Davenport residents see lower rates, averaging $1,692 per year. Des Moines premiums average $1,914.

Location affects insurance costs due to factors like local crime rates, weather patterns and rebuilding costs. Location can influence premiums, though personal credit and coverage amounts are also major contributors.

Bundling Home Insurance With Auto Insurance in Iowa

Iowa homeowners looking to maximize savings might consider bundling home insurance with auto insurance. Opting for a multipolicy bundle saves an average of 15% on the combined cost of policies. 

The savings range from $204 to $682 annually. Our comprehensive bundle analysis provides a detailed look at the best home and auto bundle companies in Iowa.

Home Insurance Discounts in Iowa

Iowa residents can take advantage of various homeowners insurance discounts to lower premiums.

  • Impact-resistant roof: Installing a roof that can withstand severe weather.
  • Home security systems: Adding burglar alarms and other security features.
  • Fire safety measures: Equipping your home with smoke detectors and fire extinguishers.

Ask the provider for further ways to save on homeowners insurance. To maximize your savings, inquire about all available discounts when requesting a quote.

FAQ: Homeowners Insurance in Iowa

On average, what is the cheapest insurer in Iowa?

In Iowa, Auto-Owners Insurance offers the lowest average premium at $1,177 per year. For more options, explore cheap national providers.

Are tornadoes in Iowa covered by homeowners insurance?

Tornadoes, a common natural disaster in Iowa, are usually covered by homeowners insurance, along with other specific coverages and exclusions.

What is the biggest factor that impacts the price of homeowners insurance in Iowa?

Credit rating is the biggest factor impacting homeowners insurance in Iowa, with a difference of $7,409 between excellent and poor credit.

In Iowa, how much, on average, can I save bundling my homeowners insurance with auto?

On average, Iowans can save around 15% per year by bundling homeowners and auto insurance.

Are floods in Iowa covered by homeowners insurance?

Flood insurance isn't included in a standard home policy. You can purchase it through the National Flood Insurance Program or a private flood insurer, and some home insurers offer it as an endorsement.
